## 7. Discussion

### 7.1 Why Existing Methods Fail on Adaptive Attacks

[~200 words]

**Krum/Trimmed Mean**: Purely geometric, one-shot aggregation. No temporal memory → fails on RMC (reconnection pattern undetected), Delayed Poisoning (gradual drift invisible), Strategy-Evolution (per-round variation looks normal).

**FLGuard**: Multi-signal but per-round. Once Byzantine threshold crossed, client blacklisted forever → vulnerable to Delayed Poisoning (delayed trigger avoids detection), RMC (new identity avoids history).

**OptiGradTrust**: RL-based trust weighting helps but greedy policy. Cannot anticipate long-horizon adaptive strategies, task-specific poisoning escapes because task isolation absent.

**Our Solution**: Temporal trajectory (multi-round memory) + task-aware filters (multi-task safety) + economic penalties (discourages re-entry) = comprehensive defense.

### 7.2 Limitations & Future Work

[~150 words]

**Limitations**:
1. Assumes synchronous FL (rounds), not asynchronous
2. Presumes aggregator honest (future: Byzantine aggregator)
3. Isolation Forest tuning (contamination parameter) dataset-dependent
4. DPoS mechanism requires client stake initialization (cold start problem)

**Future Work**:
- Asynchronous Byzantine-resilient FL
- Byzantine aggregator + multi-aggregator consensus
- Adaptive window size (vs fixed 5-round)
- Integration with blockchain for stake management

