## 8. Conclusion

Byzantine-resilient federated learning for AIOps requires defending against not just Byzantine clients, but **adaptive Byzantine strategies** that evolve over time and exploit multi-task structure. This paper introduces BR-AIOpsFL, combining trajectory-based temporal detection, task-aware aggregation, and DPoS economic slashing to provide the first provably resilient multi-task FL system for AIOps.

Our theoretical analysis proves resilience against five adaptive attack types with combined evasion probability ≈ 5×10⁻²², and experiments validate 4-10% accuracy improvements over SOTA with <4 round MTTR and <1% Byzantine evasion rate.

This work opens new frontiers in distributed AIOps: secure federated learning of anomaly detection, RCA, and predictive maintenance models without centralizing sensitive operational data. Future work extends to Byzantine aggregators, asynchronous FL, and blockchain integration.

